 Association Psychiatric Branch is the organization responsible for developing the CCMD system, which classifies and diagnoses mental disorders in China, incorporating cultural and traditional considerations>\",2\r\n2,ICD-10,\"ICD-10, the 10th edition of the International Classification of Diseases, is a globally recognized diagnostic system used for classifying diseases, health conditions, and mental disorders. It serves as a standard tool for diagnosis and treatment across various medical fields and is widely adopted internationally. ICD-10 has made significant updates to its terminology and classifications, such as removing the term \"\"hysteria\"\" due to its ambiguous meaning and retaining the term \"\"neurasthenia\"\" while limiting its use. Additionally, it has reclassified certain conditions, such as Ganser syndrome, which is categorized under \"\"other dissociative (conversion) disorders,\"\" and acute and transient psychotic disorders and severe stress reactions, which are placed under specific categories. The system also uses the term \"\"harmful use\"\" synonymously with substance abuse and categorizes mental disorders due to physical diseases under section F06. Furthermore, ICD-10 has abandoned the overarching term \"\"neurosis\"\" but has retained several subtypes related to the concept by renaming or reclassifying them, ensuring their continued presence in the classification system. This comprehensive and evolving framework is utilized by researchers and clinicians, such as Fink and 孟凡强 et al., for diagnosing conditions like somatoform disorders, making it an essential tool in global healthcare.\",22\r\n451,WORLD HEALTH ORGANIZATION,\"The World Health Organization (WHO) is a pivotal international body dedicated to global health, encompassing a wide range of initiatives and responsibilities. In 1969, WHO defined rehabilitation as the comprehensive and coordinated application of medical, educational, social, vocational, and other measures aimed at helping disabled individuals regain or improve their functions and quality of life. This definition underscores WHO's commitment to holistic health care and support for individuals with disabilities.\n\nWHO has also been instrumental in addressing mental health issues. In 1997, the organization reported that 20%-30% of undiagnosed patients in general hospitals have mental health issues, while 15%-20% of diagnosed patients have psychiatric problems. This finding highlights the critical need for mental health screening and intervention in non-psychiatric clinical settings. Additionally, WHO has conducted research revealing differences in the diagnosis of mental disorders across various cultural backgrounds and clinicians, emphasizing the importance of culturally sensitive approaches in mental health care.\n\nAs the international body responsible for the International Classification of Diseases (ICD) system, WHO plays a crucial role in classifying diseases and health problems globally, including mental disorders. This system provides a standardized framework for diagnosing and understanding health conditions worldwide. Furthermore, WHO provides global statistics on suicide rates and trends, drawing attention to the increasing prevalence of suicide and the urgent need for effective prevention strategies.\n\nThrough its diverse initiatives, WHO continues to address critical health issues, promote mental health awareness, and provide essential resources and frameworks for global health improvement.\",7\r\n121,特定恐惧症,特定恐惧症是一种对特定物体或情境感到强烈、不合理害怕或厌恶的心理障碍，包括动物恐惧、自然环境恐惧、血液-注射-损伤恐惧等类型,3\r\n1279,CIDI-C,\"The Composite International Diagnostic Interview Core Version is a standardized structured interview tool developed by WHO, corresponding to ICD-10 and DSM-IV, used for diagnosing mental disorders\",4\r\n453,DSM-III,\"The DSM-III is the third edition of the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders, published by the American Psychiatric Association in 1980, which introduced